  "prompt": "What is the difference between clause and provision?",
  "response": "A clause and a provision are both components of legal documents, but they serve different purposes and have distinct characteristics.\n\n1. **Clause:**\n   - A clause is a specific section or segment within a legal document that addresses a particular point or issue.\n   - Clauses are used to outline specific terms, conditions, obligations, rights, and responsibilities of the parties involved.\n   - They are typically numbered or labeled for easy reference.\n   - Examples of clauses include confidentiality clauses, indemnity clauses, termination clauses, etc.\n\n2. **Provision:**\n   - A provision is a broader term that refers to any stipulation, requirement, or condition within a legal document.\n   - Provisions can encompass entire clauses, paragraphs, or sections of a document.\n   - Essentially, provisions are the substantive content or terms set forth in the document.\n   - Examples of provisions include payment provisions, delivery provisions, dispute resolution provisions, etc.\n\nIn summary, a clause is a specific part of a document that addresses a detailed point, while a provision is a term or condition that the document as a whole stipulates or requires. Clauses can be considered as individual components that collectively make up the provisions of the document.",
